Details: Both agents provide cost estimation and testing effort analysis for Python migration from Alteryx workflow. AAVA_Agent delivers specific quantified estimates with detailed breakdowns ($0.75 per execution, 64 hours total effort), while General_Agent provides qualitative assessments with broader ranges (53-76 hours effort). AAVA_Agent shows superior specificity and actionability, while General_Agent acknowledges data limitations more explicitly.

Both outputs address the same core objective of estimating costs and testing effort for Alteryx-to-Python migration. AAVA_Agent focuses on specific monetary costs and precise hour estimates, while General_Agent emphasizes the lack of explicit pricing data and provides ranges. Both cover runtime costs, manual fixes, testing effort, and API costs. The semantic intent aligns well but with different approaches to uncertainty handling.

Both outputs follow similar three-section structure: 1) Cost Estimation with Python Runtime Cost subsection, 2) Code Fixing and Testing Effort Estimation, 3) API Call Cost. AAVA_Agent uses more granular subsections (1.1, 2.1) and detailed breakdowns, while General_Agent uses numbered lists with bullet points. Both maintain logical flow from costs to effort to API pricing.

AAVA_Agent output is syntactically well-formed with proper markdown structure, consistent formatting, and no broken references. Minor issue: API cost format 'apiCost: 0.002 USD' could be more descriptive. All calculations and estimates are internally consistent.

General_Agent output has proper structure and formatting. Minor issues include: inconsistent bullet point formatting in lines 8-15, and the duplicate content section at the end (lines 35-50) which appears redundant. Otherwise syntactically correct.
Average correctness score of both agents. Both outputs are syntactically sound with minor formatting inconsistencies.
